id: pm-n7rr
title: "CLI surface simplification: noun-verb consolidation to a minimal agent-first command grammar (zero feature loss)"
description: "Consolidate the ~60 top-level pm commands into a minimal, predictable noun-verb grammar so agents can operate the full surface from a small command set. Every existing feature and flag survives; removed spellings live on as hidden back-compat aliases. Duplicate check: searched simplify/consolidation/tiered-help/alias items — only closed historical polish (pm-5k2w, pm-rnpb) matched; no open overlap."
type: Epic
status: open
priority: 1
tags[5]: agent-ux,"area:cli","area:contracts",refactor,simplification
created_at: "2026-07-05T04:51:21.783Z"
updated_at: "2026-07-05T08:02:45.439Z"
author: maintainer-agent
estimated_minutes: 2400
acceptance_criteria: Top-level command list fits one help screen (~15 nouns); every pre-existing command spelling still works (hidden alias shims + deprecation notice); contracts/MCP/completions/docs regenerated with zero feature regression; agent token cost of 'pm --help' + contracts measurably reduced; all existing tests pass unchanged (aliases keep old spellings valid)
goal: project management = context management
objective: Shrink the top-level command surface (~60 -> ~15 nouns) without removing any feature or functionality
value: Agents discover and operate pm with less context; help/contract payloads shrink; fewer wrong-command retries
why_now: "The command surface has grown command-by-command to ~60 top-level entries (8 list-* variants, 4 history commands, 4 package-lifecycle commands, 3 lifecycle aliases, 3 calendar shortcuts); agents report the CLI is getting too complicated"
parent: pm-mpbb
risk: medium
confidence: high
comments[1]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-05T08:02:33.747Z",codex-sdk-agent,"Scope alignment evidence: PR #431 review caught that the target-surface body omitted append from item facets. Updated the live epic body through pm update so the consolidation grammar includes comments/notes/learnings/files/docs/deps/append/test."
notes[2]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-05T04:55:44.581Z",maintainer-agent,"Brainstorm census 2026-07-05 — current surface is ~60 top-level commands. Redundancy clusters found; 8 list-* status variants (list/all/draft/open/in-progress/blocked/closed/canceled), 5 history-family commands (history/history-redact/history-repair/history-compact/activity) plus restore, 4 package-lifecycle commands (extension/package/install/upgrade — extension and package are already partial synonyms), 3 lifecycle sugar commands (start-task/pause-task/close-task) duplicating claim/release/close+status, 3 calendar shortcuts (meet/event/remind) duplicating create with presets, 6 diagnostics commands (stats/health/validate/gc/telemetry/eval). Consolidating just these clusters removes ~24 top-level entries with zero feature loss."
  "2026-07-05T04:55:44.951Z",maintainer-agent,"Sequencing decision — alias shim layer (pm-0z7n) is the shared foundation and must land first after ADR pm-pbyu acceptance; each cluster task then becomes a mechanical table edit + spelling-parity spec. Token baseline (pm-a22j) runs before any change so the epic has measurable before/after evidence. Every rename must walk the full wiring checklist (commands/index, register-mutation, mcp/server, sdk/cli-contracts, contracts.ts, completions x3 shells, docs, vitest.config, contracts:update)."
learnings[1]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-05T04:55:45.356Z",maintainer-agent,Surface growth pattern learned from history; features were added as new top-level commands because that was the path of least resistance in Commander registration — the grammar ADR plus contracts-generated help removes that incentive by making subcommand addition cheaper than top-level addition.
body: "## Charter\nReduce cognitive surface, not capability. The pm CLI keeps 100% of its features but presents them behind a small noun-verb grammar. This epic is the umbrella for the brainstormed consolidation clusters (each a child item) and the ADR that fixes the grammar rules.\n\n## Grammar principles (brainstorm summary — ADR child formalizes)\n1. Noun-first: one top-level command per domain noun (item lifecycle, list, history, package, schema, config, profile, plan, search, ops/diagnostics).\n2. Verbs/facets are subcommands or flags, never new top-level commands.\n3. Status/type projections are flags (--status, --type), not command variants.\n4. Sugar commands (shortcuts, lifecycle aliases) are hidden aliases or package-provided, never core surface.\n5. Nothing is deleted: every current spelling keeps working via an alias shim that prints a one-line migration hint (suppressible via config).\n6. Contracts are the source of truth: help tiers, completions, MCP tools, and docs are all generated from the same contract table.\n\n## Target surface (~15 nouns)\ninit, config, schema, profile, package (extension/install/upgrade), create (+meet/event/remind sugar), get, list (all status variants), update (update-many), close (close-many/delete), claim (release/start/pause), item facets (comments/notes/learnings/files/docs/deps/append/test), history (restore/redact/repair/compact/activity), search, plan, context (next/focus), ops (stats/health/validate/gc/telemetry/eval), contracts, help.\n\n## Relationship to SDK-first epic\nConsolidation is implemented on top of the SDK-first primitives (see linked epic under pm-ugqx): command shims become thin SDK calls, which is what makes the alias layer cheap and regression-safe.\n\n## Cluster index update (audit 2026-07-05, second pass)\nThree target-surface clusters previously had no implementing child; filed: pm-yql1 (item annotation facets), pm-ik19 (bulk/destructive lifecycle variants), pm-kcs4 (context/next/focus navigation noun). ADR pm-pbyu ownership resolution for the earlier mapping conflicts: restore belongs under history because it replays audited history state, while eval belongs under ops because it is a diagnostic/evaluation surface rather than a primary search query primitive."
